1. Variables and Strings
Declared variables using let
Performed string operations:
str.length
str.toUpperCase()
str.toLowerCase()
str.substring(1, 5)

Used to get length, change case, and extract part of a string.

2. Arithmetic Operations

Performed basic math:

a + b
a - b
a * b
a / b
a % b

Used for addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and remainder.

3. Comparison (Logical Operations)

Checked conditions:

a > b
a < b
a == b
a != b
a >= b
a <= b

Returns boolean values (true or false).

4. Objects

Created an object:

let obj = { name, age, city };

Accessed properties using dot notation:

obj.name
obj.age
obj.city
5. Dynamic Typing

Variable type can change:

let str2 = "Aryan";
str2 = 23;

JavaScript allows changing data types at runtime.

6. Functions

Simple function for addition:

function add(a, b) {
    return a + b;
}
7. const, let, var (Scope)
const → fixed value
let → block scoped
var → function scoped (can leak outside block)

Example shows difference between block scope and global scope.

8. Arrays
let arr = [1, "Aaryan", 3, true, 5];

Stores mixed data types.

9. Conditions

If-else example:

if (i > j) { ... } else { ... }

Used for decision making.

10. Switch Case
switch(choice) {
    case "A":
    case "B":
    default:
}

Used for multiple conditions.

11. Type Checking
typeof variable

Used to check data type of values.

12. Loop with Condition
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    if(typeof arr[i] === "number") {
        console.log(arr[i]);
    }
}

Loops through array and prints only numbers.